9144 Queens Boulevard, south side, between Woodhaven Boulevard and Eliot Avenue, showing Mrs. Raymond's House, built at the end of the eighteenth century. These views show the house on a temporary site across the street from the above location, having been placed there temporarily during the widening of the south side of Queens Boulevard. Eugene L. Armbruster states that the original location of the dwelling was at 49 Queens Boulevard.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection

Queens Boulevard, west side, between Woodhaven Boulevard and Eliot Avenue, showing three views of the Louis Bolsen house, still owned by him in 1924. It was erected on the site of the Gottlieb Reichert house which was destroyed by fire. Other owners of this property were H. Reickers, 1801; and Philip Reichert, 1891(?). Partially seen at the right foreground of view number three is the section of Mrs. Raymond's house which stood formerly at number 49 Queens Boulevard, opposite the Horan house. It is to be placed on the opposite side of the Boulevard near the hothouses in the foreground beyond the truck seen at the
left.
